1. INTENT
---------------------------------------------
Attach additional responsibilities to an object dynamically.

👉 Add features at runtime WITHOUT modifying existing class.

=============================================

2. REAL-WORLD ANALOGY
---------------------------------------------
- Pizza toppings (cheese, olives, mushrooms)
- Coffee customization (milk, sugar, syrup)
- Logging / encryption / compression layers
- C++ IO streams (fstream decorators internally)

=============================================

3. KEY IDEA (MOST IMPORTANT)
---------------------------------------------
Wrap objects inside objects repeatedly.

Example:
PlainPizza → Cheese → Olives → ExtraCheese

This forms a CHAIN of decorators.

=============================================

4. PROBLEM WITHOUT DECORATOR
---------------------------------------------
- Class explosion problem:
  PizzaWithCheese
  PizzaWithCheeseOlives
  PizzaWithCheeseOlivesMushroom ...

- Not flexible at runtime
- Violates Open/Closed Principle

=============================================

5. STRUCTURE
---------------------------------------------

1. Component (Interface)
   - Pizza (base interface)

2. Concrete Component
   - PlainPizza

3. Decorator Base Class
   - Has-a + Is-a relationship
   - Holds pointer to base component

4. Concrete Decorators
   - Cheese, Olives, etc.

=============================================

6. BENEFITS
---------------------------------------------
✔ Dynamic behavior addition
✔ No modification of base class
✔ Avoid subclass explosion
✔ Follows Open/Closed Principle
✔ Flexible chaining of features

=============================================

7. DRAWBACKS
---------------------------------------------
❌ Many wrapper objects
❌ Debugging becomes harder (deep chains)
❌ Memory management complexity (important in C++)

=============================================

8. INTERVIEW KEY POINTS
---------------------------------------------
✔ Uses composition (HAS-A relationship)
✔ Runtime behavior modification
✔ Each decorator is same type as base (IS-A)
✔ Recursive structure
✔ Used in streams, middleware, UI systems

=============================================

9. CRITICAL C++ NOTE (IMPORTANT ADDITION)
---------------------------------------------
👉 Current code uses RAW POINTERS
In real production C++:
✔ Prefer smart pointers (unique_ptr/shared_ptr)
to avoid memory leaks

=============================================

10. ONE-LINE DEFINITION
---------------------------------------------
Decorator pattern dynamically adds behavior to an object by wrapping it inside other objects of the same type.

=============================================

11. MEMORY TRICK
---------------------------------------------
Decorator = "Layers on top of object"

=============================================

12. IMPLEMENTATION (YOUR CODE - KEPT + COMPLETE)
---------------------------------------------
#include <iostream>

// Base Component (Abstract Pizza)
class Pizza {
public:
    virtual ~Pizza() = default;
    virtual std::string getDescription() const = 0;
    virtual double getCost() const = 0;
};

// Concrete Component (Plain Pizza)
class PlainPizza : public Pizza {
public:
    std::string getDescription() const override {
        return "Plain Pizza";
    }

    double getCost() const override {
        return 5.0; // Base price
    }
};

// Decorator Base Class
class PizzaDecorator : public Pizza {
protected:
    Pizza* pizza; // wrapped object

public:
    PizzaDecorator(Pizza* p) : pizza(p) {}

    std::string getDescription() const override {
        return pizza->getDescription();
    }

    double getCost() const override {
        return pizza->getCost();
    }
};

// Concrete Decorator 1
class Cheese : public PizzaDecorator {
public:
    Cheese(Pizza* p) : PizzaDecorator(p) {}

    std::string getDescription() const override {
        return pizza->getDescription() + ", Cheese";
    }

    double getCost() const override {
        return pizza->getCost() + 2.0;
    }
};

// Concrete Decorator 2
class Olives : public PizzaDecorator {
public:
    Olives(Pizza* p) : PizzaDecorator(p) {}

    std::string getDescription() const override {
        return pizza->getDescription() + ", Olives";
    }

    double getCost() const override {
        return pizza->getCost() + 1.5;
    }
};

// Main function
int main() {

    Pizza* pizza = new PlainPizza();
    std::cout << pizza->getDescription()
              << " -> $" << pizza->getCost() << std::endl;

    pizza = new Cheese(pizza);
    std::cout << pizza->getDescription()
              << " -> $" << pizza->getCost() << std::endl;

    pizza = new Olives(pizza);
    std::cout << pizza->getDescription()
              << " -> $" << pizza->getCost() << std::endl;

    delete pizza;
    return 0;
}
